moods = ['sadness', 'anger', 'love', 'surprise', 'fear', 'joy']
moods_int2str = {}
moods_str2int = {}
for mood in moods:
    fc = df['label_name'] == mood
    class_num = df.loc[fc, 'label'].values[0]
    moods_str2int[mood] = class_num
    moods_int2str[class_num] = mood

11.2 Create the BentoML API Service
    

  • https://docs.bentoml.org/en/latest/concepts/service.html
      

    • Inference APIs define how the service functionality can be called remotely. A service can have one or more APIs. An API consists of its input/output specs and a callback function. read the docs
      • 

    

    • 

  • I think if I have 2 apis, for example, one for predict, one for classification, it can be done inside one service.py by creating two @svc.api functions.
    • 























11.2.1 Create Service.py








# save the code in this cell to "service.py"
import bentoml
import numpy as np
from bentoml.io import NumpyNdarray, Text

tag = bentoml.models.get("emotion_detection_lr:latest")
class_labels_d = tag.custom_objects.get('class_labels_d')

# create a bentoml runner from a stored bentoml model
# emotion_detection_lr_clf_runner = bentoml.models.get("emotion_detection_lr:latest").to_runner()
emotion_detection_lr_clf_runner = tag.to_runner()

# Create a BentoML Service object
# The service name will become the name of the Bento.
svc = bentoml.Service("emotion_detection_lr_classifier", runners=[emotion_detection_lr_clf_runner])

@svc.api(input=Text(), output=Text())
def classifyemotion(input_text: str) -> str:
    # this function name, 'classify' will be transformed into the HTTP endpoint /classify
    # but it can also be customised, see: https://docs.bentoml.org/en/latest/concepts/service.html
    # e.g. in the @svc.api decorator, adddir
    # route="/v2/models/my_model/versions/v0/infer",
    # print('\n\n')
    # print(type(input_text), input_text)
    # print('\n\n')
    
 
    class_num = emotion_detection_lr_clf_runner.predict.run([input_text])[0]
    class_lbl = class_labels_d.get(class_num)
    
    # print('\n\n')
    # print(type(class_lbl), ' -- ', class_lbl)
    # print('\n\n')
    # return "world says hello"    
    return class_lbl













11.2.2 Start the Endpoint








# at cmdline run the following to get the endpoint up

$> bentoml serve service.py:svc --reload  # svc is the var that was declared in service.py (above)
                                          # if you used another var name, then the above cmd line code needs to reflect it
# The --reload tags ensures that BentoML detects changes made to your script without needing to restart the server.

# once the service starts: http://localhost:3000/ to see the API Docs

# test with curl command:
curl -X POST -H "accept: text/plain" -H "content-type: text/plain" --data "who are you?" http://127.0.0.1:3000/classifyemotion

12. Build a Bento
    

  • https://towardsdatascience.com/comprehensive-guide-to-deploying-any-ml-model-as-apis-with-python-and-aws-lambda-b441d257f1ec
    • 

  • Bento is a term introduced by BentoML that refers to an archive that contains everything needed to make our API work  in a unified format
    • 

  • Inside a Bento, there will be instructions on building a Docker image and the dependencies of our API model
    • 

  • https://docs.bentoml.org/en/latest/concepts/bento.html
    • 























12.1 Create bentofile.yaml
    

  • https://docs.bentoml.org/en/latest/concepts/bento.html
    • 

  • We start building the Bento by creating a bentofile.yaml file (the service name should be the same as our service.py script) and in the same directory level as our scripts. It will look like below:
    • 



















In[]:






service: "service.py:svc"  # Same as the argument passed to `bentoml serve`
labels:
    owner: Richard Chai
    stage: dev

13. Create Docker Image using Bento








$ bentoml containerize emotion_detection_lr_classifier:2d37jtlqxg6uzxcg

if successful, the following will appear:





















To run your newly built Bento container, run:
    docker run --rm -p 3000:3000 emotion_detection_lr_classifier:2d37jtlqxg6uzxcg













13.1 Create Docker container and Test it








$> docker run --rm -p 3000:3000 emotion_detection_lr_classifier:2d37jtlqxg6uzxcg

add -d to run docker in detach mode and see other commands to stop the container https://docs.docker.com/language/golang/run-containers/

$> docker run -d --rm -p 3000:3000 emotion_detection_lr_classifier:2d37jtlqxg6uzxcg













13.1.2 Get Predictions from the Running Docker Container using curl








curl -X POST -H "accept: text/plain" -H "content-type: text/plain" --data "who are you?" http://127.0.0.1:3000/classifyemotion



































Note that the training dataset does not contain the emotion "neutral", instead if a text looks like it should be "neutral",
it will be classified as "joy", i.e. neural is not a negative sentiment, neither is it positive, but let's put it as positive since we
don't have a neutral emotion to put it in.






















13.1.3 Get Predictions from the Running Docker Container using Python code


















In[34]:






# get_predictions.py
import json
import requests
import numpy as np

endpoint = "http://127.0.0.1:3000/classifyemotion"

X_data = "Today is a super duper great day!"  

response = requests.post(endpoint, 
                         headers={
                             "accept": "text/plain", 
                             "content-type": "text/plain"
                         }, 
                         data=X_data)
print('-'*50)
print(type(response))
print(response)
print(response.text)
print()

























--------------------------------------------------
<class 'requests.models.Response'>
<Response [200]>
joy

rchai/text-emotion-detection













13.2.2 Tag the Local Image first (IMPORTANT)








# next, tag the local image
$> docker tag emotion_detection_lr_classifier:2d37jtlqxg6uzxcg rchai/text-emotion-detection:trained_on_dair-ai_emotion

# to view: $> docker images
# local image name:                     emotion_detection_lr_classifier
# local image tag for that image name:  ewbzyp3l6oibtxcg
# online docker hub repo name:          rchai/text-emotion-detection
# the tag name that will appear in the online repo: myfirstimagepush  # you can name this anything













13.2.3 Push the locally tagged image to dockerhub repo








# Next, push the local image which has been tagged to the online repo

$> docker push rchai/text-emotion-detection:trained_on_dair-ai_emotion















































































13.3 Pull Docker Image from Docker Hub and use it to classify emotions








$> docker login
